<br>
 In such cases you usually fight mobs on the ground. For various reasons, you must not send your pet on attack directly from the  wall to the ground :<br>
 - when you're on wall, you might not be sure that the main assist has targeted the correct mob, and it always happen from time to time to have chainpuller targeting a wrong mob for some time, as mouse strafing or clicking on the ground can select some mob far away.<br>
 - if your pet is not guarding directly above the place where the chainpuller is (if the chainpuller is somewhat on the left for instance), sending the pet on attack might cause aggro by bad pathing.<br>
<br>
 So you need to put your pet on follow mode, and move slowly to the ground near the chainpuller while keeping your pet in tight range, then send your pet on attack. This means after the fight you will need to bring him up again somewhere not far from the top of the wall and make him guard again.<br>
<br>
 So provided you're in charge either of annul or of malosi, you migth as well forget using a pet. Even if you're not, it's pretty much boring to use one on wall.<br>
<br>
Once the camp is set on the ground, though, either on the ground near wall or in maestro hall, there is no reason for not using a pet. The only thing for maestro hall is that the camp must be set in  front of the throne far from walls, and the pulls must be made to the opposite wall (the one that the throne faces) the throne room. That will avoid any pathing problems.<br>
<br>
 I don't know how PoH is now, but pre changes, most non very experienced guilds would stay on the wall for a long time, while more experienced ones would fight on ground from the very beginning, thus allowing pets.<br>
<br>
 And don't be too upset if your raidleader or your guildmates don't let you use a pet anywhere in PoH. Mages are still very useful without pets, with best damage shields, mod rods, CoH at 55, annul magic, etc.. Discuss it quietly with the raidleader once the raid is over if you think pets should have been allowed when they were not. He might allow them next time.<br>
